Just a reminder that disability isn’t a bad or dirty word. 😉

social_posts.post_text: Learning to levitate some at the @levitate.sport clinic yesterday! I haven’t done box jumps in half a decade, this was too much fun. 😉

My two big pups, Sophie and Leo, are my life - but taking care of a couple of large dogs as an amputee living alone definitely poses some challenges. There are many days when I can’t use my leg, when I’m on crutches or in a chair.

Along with the normal things like making sure they get enough exercise, there are the other problems I’d never think of before losing my leg. Things like getting heavy dog food bags into the house on days when I can’t use my prosthesis. Or the mobility risk that dog hair brings between gathering on the bottom of my prosthetic foot shell (which I can’t feel, so slipping becomes a real danger). 

I often get asked how I take care of them - so I made a new video up on YouTube now all about how I’ve adapted my life to be able to properly take care of these two perfect mongrels. 😉 Link in my bio if you’d like to check it out!

#Dogs #GSD #DogsOfIG #Adapt #Amputee #AmputeeProblems #Prosthetic #ProstheticLeg

I did something very outside my comfort zone this past month: a boudoir shoot with all of my mobility aids.

I’ve really struggled this year to accept using a wheelchair as simply a tool without judgement. One day I got a text about a Christmas special on a boudoir shoot and got the idea to do one with my wheelchair, prosthetic - and most intimidating of all for me - no leg.

While I’m fine showing up on the internet showing my chair or nubbin’, in real life, with people I’m close to, I still experience a lot of discomfort and sometimes shame or wanting to hide. So I took a huge leap and booked the shoot.

And oh my gosh - it helped. It was so incredible finding different angles and photos in such a different context for me that involved my chair, etc. At the start of the shoot I was petrified, but by the end I was excited.

This was a genuinely healing, beautiful experience for me. Sometimes thinking outside of the box when it comes to accepting ourselves and our lives, the way they are, pays off. 💜

I’m really grateful to @colorado_springs_boudoir for such a safe, amazing environment, and to my sweet friend @shayleemeurer for coming with me to film some behind the scenes! A full video about the experience is live on YouTube now.

If you’ve ever thought about doing something like this, I can’t recommend it highly enough when it comes to embracing the skin you are in. 💜

YET. A word I keep coming back to especially this year. In the confusing or dark moments, when I have no idea how to make it - I return to it.

I can’t see a way through this - yet. I don’t have a f*cking clue how to make it - yet. I’m not sure - yet. I don’t know what to do - yet. The list goes on.

As permanent or hopeless as some things feel, they aren’t. Things shift, change, and the darkness does eventually lift.

So as is my habit, I got it inked on me to remind me when I forget. 💜 Thank you @dez_tattoos for your tattoo magic, as always. 😉

#Yet #Tattoo #Hope

The day before Christmas Eve this past year, I broke.
 
I’ve always joked about mental breakdowns, but this is the first time I think I can say I actually fell the f*ck apart. Everything hurt too much. The daily chronic pain in my body combined with a heaping and dark dose of depression and emotional pain, trauma, and change from this year and it felt like too much – because it was. 
 
I’m lucky that I have a few dear people in my life who will answer the phone at late hours, one of whom came over and sat with me late into the night to make sure I was okay. One piece of advice that really stuck with me was this: if the life you’re living right now isn’t worth the pain, find something that is. For whatever reason, that resonated with me in a way that I can’t shake.
 
Since then, I’ve begun to work on finding things worth the pain.
 
Lately, that’s looked like trying a lot of new things, and saying no to a whole lot. 
 
I started lifting weights again. 
Got a lot of new tattoos because I love them, one a week for awhile there so I’d have something to look forward to each week. 
Enrolled in a jiujitsu competition that I’m training hard for. 
Started taking a pole dancing/fitness class, which I’ve always wanted to do but was too intimidated to start. 
Started cooking food for myself. 
Said no to a lot of social engagements, work opportunities, etc.
And started *actually* prioritizing things that keep me sane, and around.
 
I don’t have a handle on things yet and there are many moments when the overall pain feels suffocating. Life feels like a bunch of bullsh*t. But, I’m taking steps forward to build a life I want to remain a part of and will keep doing so.
 
If it feels like it isn’t worth it, keep searching. The world is a huge place. We all contain multitudes.

I sat down to film a nice and composed video about the frustrations of living in a dysfunctional body - but what came out instead was just a lot of anger. 

The vast majority of the time, I can roll with all of it. I’m okay. I adjust, I modify, I move on - no problem. But every now and again all the little things build up and the underlying rage becomes so palpable.

I live in a body that is always in pain. And has been the majority of my life. Most recently, my leg has started having some odd issues (that I’m sure are solvable) but are preventing me from some things I really wanted to do and have been looking forward to. Its another shift, another adjustment - and sometimes I just really wish things were more “normal.”

I will be just fine - and adjust, and continue on. But I’m trying to learn to acknowledge the frustration and anger, feel it, and let it pass on instead of shoving it down.

🎶 I can take myself dancing… 🎶
I’ve always been super interested in pole dance and fitness but was always way too intimidated to try (even when I had two legs). This past month I had a day where I said “screw it, what’s the worst that could happen?” and showed up to a class same day.

I’m SO GLAD I did. It is so much fun and super athletically challenging. I wasn’t sure if I’d even be able to do anything with my one side being prosthetic (skin contact, ankle bend, and knee bending are really important in pole, neither of which I can do well on that side!) - but like almost everything else, modifications make it totally do-able. Also having the pole relieves a lot of pressure on my leg!

I still have zero clue what I’m doing, but it has been such a blast to try learning something new & challenging and I’m going to keep taking classes! 💜

This first photo popped up on my timeline from four years ago today. This was the first time I was “back on the mats” after my first amputation surgery. I wasn’t rolling or training that day as I was awaiting further surgery - but I remember how terrified I was to crutch into the gym.

I felt weak. I felt less. I felt super self conscious. I didn’t want to come in because all of these people had worked with me when I had my right foot, and now I looked so different (in retrospect, I’m certain none of them cared - it was just my own self doubt and insecurity). 

I wasn’t sure if I’d ever really return to training because I was really intimidated by how much I’d have to relearn and how different it would feel…so I didn’t really come back for years - until 2022. I’m so ridiculously thankful that I did.

Now, four years later, I’m learning more and more how to use my specific body as a tool and weapon in Jiujitsu. I don’t think I would say this with anything else I’ve ever tried, but in jiujitsu I’m not sure that missing my leg below the knee is a real disadvantage (long term). There’s a lot that I can’t do -  but there’s also a lot of things that I can do that no one else (with two legs!) can do when it comes to passes, submissions, etc. 

It’s a huge learning curve and process and all my coaches and training partners have been AMAZING and so creative and dedicated in helping me learn what to do with my body. To ALL of you - thank you, so much. 💜

I now feel really comfortable and excited on the mats. It’s one of very few places that I feel free. When I’m rolling, the rest of the world disappears. Learning what my body can do is really cool.

Excited to continue this journey. 💜 Training for my first competition post-amputation coming up in March. 🤼‍♀️

Learning how to make peace with reality, grieve what I wanted that will never be, while readjusting my focus on what I now dream of the future to be…is hard. 

I’ve recently seen a lot of short inspirational videos about “the only thing standing between you and your dream life is YOU! You just have to work and make it happen!”

…but what happens when that isn’t the case? The life I dream of doesn’t involve pain. Doesn’t involve my leg being a factor and an adjustment in everything. Doesn’t include more surgeries. Doesn’t involve the reality of the body that I actually live in. If I keep those dreams, I’m going to increase unnecessary suffering - because they will never be reality.

So I’m in the mud of the process of trying to grapple and grieve a reality that is difficult for me to make peace with while also thinking up a new dream life and direction - one that I still want, one that just looks a little bit different. 💜

#Dreams #DreamLife #Grief #Grieving #Chronic #ChronicPain #Amputee

I told myself that I’d give myself a year.

A year came and went, and this weekend it was time to go through all the boxes. I spent a couple of days going through remnants of life that doesn’t exist anymore. Boxes that were packed in a rush, inconsequential mail left on the shared kitchen counter stuffed into corners, pictures - a snapshot of what was. 

It was painful, uncomfortable, freeing and healing. Divorce is miserable, regardless of the circumstances that cause it. Now everything that is in my house are items that are relevant to life as it is now for me - and I’m really grateful for that.

“Look, I assumed that people in wheelchairs also had to buy bras and buy underwear, I didn’t know that we needed to see that IN OUR FACE. I didn’t know that now we’re gonna have to look forward to campaigns where women that are in wheelchairs are now wearing bras and underwear…because we as a society just cannot get to the bottom of our ridiculousness.”

The above was one of many comments made by Candice Owens, @realcandaceowens , a public persona with millions of followers, in a recent video while commenting on an ad that featured a women, sitting in a wheelchair, modeling underwear (featured in the last slide). Candice made it incredibly clear both in her initial video & follow up response that models with disabilities shouldn’t exist in these spaces…these spaces being, advertising in general. 

Ew, gross, who needs to see that? (My own sarcasm)

She ended the segment by noting that she believed women in wheelchairs would back her up - I assure you, that’s not the case.

My first YouTube video of 2023 is up discussing her comments and more importantly her response to the feedback she received. You can find it on my YouTube channel or by following the link in my bio. 🦽

#CandiceOwens #Wheelchair #Amputee

One year ago today I had to say goodbye to my little pup, Sully. He had just turned ten months old.

When my dog Monkey passed away in 2021, it left a giant hole in my life. My then-partner and I stumbled across this little guy at an adoption fair (with no intention of adopting another dog, but you know how these things go…). He started his little adventurous life on the islands of Turks & Caicos when a vacationing family found out he had severe heart issues and transferred him back to the US for veterinary help. 
 
When he was four months old, he was stable enough to go home with a new family with the understanding that his time on earth was going to be limited. We didn’t know how long he’d have – it could be weeks, months, or years.
 
We adopted him and committed to giving him the best darn life a puppy could have and he did. I got to have six months as his mom – and the time he had was beautiful. His condition progressed really quickly, and by April it became apparent that no treatments were working. It was time to say goodbye.
 
Sully was a huge lesson in loving what you have when you have it. The age old question of, “is it better to have loved and lost then never to have loved at all?” was again answered with a resounding yes - it absolutely is. Loss is painful and tears you apart - but loving it still worth it.

He brought so much joy and love to my life. I know no dog lives forever – but having him and understanding in a more visceral way that every day could be his last led me to really cherish the moments he was here. 
 
Sophie adored him – she doesn’t get along great with other dogs, but they palled around every day immediately. He was an absolute cuddle bug, a GOOF, a bundle of sweet energy, and loved hopping up on his hind legs when getting excited for dinner. Miss you little guy. 🐾

Happy #DisabilityPride month! 🎉 The first time I heard July was Disability Pride Month it was a little confusing to me. The idea of being proud of something that initially felt like a hinderance to my life, something I didn’t ask for nor want, didn’t click for me. 

Looking into it, I learned that Disability Pride exists to honor the experience, struggles, history, and achievements of our disabled community. And being a part of this community is something I am SO proud, and honored, to be in. The tenacity, grace, and welcoming that this community holds is something I will always be grateful for and in awe of. 💜

Disability Pride Month is a time to come together and share what disability means to you - to celebrate the victories and also acknowledge that there is much to be done still when it comes to accessibility in our communities. I encourage you to #PassThePride and share what Disability Pride Month means to you! 👏 I challenge @annikatheamputee , @alex1leg , and @amputay_ to share, if you feels so inclined. ☺️

I think there is a lot of freedom to be found in letting go of the idea that everything has a value of “good” or “bad”. Right or wrong. Black or white. Oftentimes, things just…are. They’re choices.

Growing up, I was a taught through the lens of religion to see every single thought, choice, action as one extreme or the other. Every aspect of the world held the label. In some ways its comforting believing everything is one way or the other - because if you’re on the “right” path, you know where you stand. But not every thing is a moral statement. And that way of thinking stops growth, promotes judgement to ourselves and others, and can leave us feeling absolutely paralyzed.

One of the most helpful things I’ve gained from going to therapy in the past couple of years is the ability to see a lot more as neutral. It isn’t right or wrong to have that conversation - there are consequences on both sides, consider them, and make a choice. Moving to a different city isn’t good or bad - its a choice, on either side there will be repercussions. Leaving a relationship isn’t morally wrong or right - I get to decide what is the best and healthiest thing for my life, and either way, there will be ramifications. They’re just choices, not statements on our moral character or value as human beings.

Opening up a more neutral way of thinking has helped me to remove a lot of the constant, oppressive judgement I was leveling against myself every second of every day. I have more compassion towards my choices and thoughts. Obviously, some things are still morally good, and others we can agree are morally bad. There is a place for that kind of thinking in some situations - but I’d argue that most things are just living.

What do you think - do you agree or disagree? This video is from a clip of the @turbodudepodcast that I host with my one of my best friends @life_of_palos , check it out if you feel so inclined. 😊

5 years ago today I walked into a hospital with two legs and rolled out with one. This is the first “ampu-versary” that I feel more grief than anything. 

Though it was the best choice and one I’m grateful I made, I’m sad that I ever had to make it. 

I hurt for the teenager I was living from surgery to surgery, on crutches, and in a lot of pain. 
I grieve for the young adult I was on handfuls of painkillers, watching activities I loved become less and less as my ankle became worse. 
I feel for the twenty-seven year old I was when I had to make an impossible decision to cut off a body part for even a chance of a more functional life with less pain. 
And I grieve for a life I won’t ever have, an imagined one where my life isn’t largely dictated by pain and adaptation to my body. 

I am deeply grateful for my life and what I’ve been able to do, and very sad and heavy at once. Grief is weird and comes in unexpected waves. Thank you for so many of you who have been here for so much of this part of my story. 💜

October 30th is historically the hardest day of the year for me. Twelve years ago I experienced the culmination of sexual, physical, spiritual and emotional trauma on this day that fundamentally changed every aspect of my life and shattered what I knew to be just about every part of my identity and worldview. 

Every year it feels a little different. 

On the tenth anniversary, I was celebratory, happy and proud. 

On the eleventh, I couldn’t breathe. 

And today, I feel the grief of what was lost and fear, mixed with a good deal of hope and contentment. 

I’m proud of who I am now while still recognizing and mourning what was lost and the effects that still linger to this day.

When events happen that shatter us - where there is a very definite “before” and “after” in our lives - things will never go back to the way they were. Its unfair, it hurts, its confusing, it never fully goes away. 

But we get to make choices for who we are going to be and how we’re going to move through it. We get to forge a new life.

I’m grateful that I’ve had the chance to do that and had a lot of support along the way. 💜

Even if you or your friends might not do drugs, carrying an overdose reversal medication could save someone’s life. Keep yourself and your friends safe.

This isn’t a revolutionary concept, but it helped me come to terms with what being disabled meant to me. So often we assign value to things that are neutral. Disability simply means living in a world that is built for a person with different abilities. It means constant adaptation - it doesn’t mean anything about who you are as a human being or the value that you bring. 💜

Prosthetic companies - there’s gotta be a more discreet way to do this. 😆 While there is a requirement for labeling medical equipment, there are a lot of ways I believe this could be done without making patients walking advertisements…? Anyone else feel this way?
